Overview

  • two data science outcomes to avoid
  • write production level code
  • put insight on the top of presentation hiearchy
  • make bold statements on the top of visual hiearchy
  • strive for a reasonable insight-to-action conversion ratio

Two types of data scientists

  • Type B for building

  • Type A for analytics

Two outcomes to avoid

  • Type B: models do not get into production system
  • Type A: insight do not result in an action

Writing production level code

  • writing modular, resuable code
  • documentation and commenting
  • version control
  • testing
  • logging

An example of unit testing

If data scientists can improve model deployment through
writing production level code, what could data scientists
do to convert insight into action?

“Statisticians, like artists, have the bad habit of
falling in love with their models.” - George Box

“You must invert what you learned in school about reasoning and writing. You learned to start with a warm-up, then reason deductively, starting from first principles and reaching a conclusion. Business readers have no time for warm-ups and lack the patience for extended reasoning unless
they know the payoff up front. So start with bold statements and conclusions. Then follow with the reasoning that got you there. That way, readers who don’t read the whole document will still benefit from reading your conclusion.” – Josh Bernoff, Writing Without Bullshit

Put insight on the top of presentation hiearchy

“A picture is worth a thousand words”

“The greatest value of a picture is when it forces us to notice
what we never expected to see” – John Tukey, Exploratory Data Analysis

Recommended books

Storytelling with Data

Data Points: Visualization That Means Something

“pull one hair and the whole body is affected” – Chinese proverb

“Most decisions should probably be made with somewhere around 70% of the information you wish you had. If you wait for 90%, in most cases, you’re probably being slow. Plus, either way, you need to be good at quickly recognizing and correcting bad decisions. If you’re good at course correcting, being wrong may be less costly than you think, whereas being slow is going to be expensive for sure.” – Jeff Bezos

“The best decisions are made by an idea meritocracy with believability-weighted decision making, in which the most capable people work through their disagreements with other capable people who have thought independently about what is true and what to do about it.” – Ray Dalio, Principles

Strive for a reasonable insight-to-action conversion ratio

Summary

Insight is one essential output of Data Science work. We search for insight in data because we want insight to help us make this world a better place. Converting insight into action is the way to materialize valuable insight.

  • put insight on the top of presentation hiearchy
  • make bold statements on the top of visual hiearchy
  • strive for a reasonable insight-to-action conversion ratio

Thank you for your attention!
